> Mini Project: Provision EC2 Instance using Copilot in Vibe Mode :
=====================================================================
   This mini project is our first hands-on experience with AI-driven Infrastructure as Code. The goal is to understand how we can use natural language and AI assistance to generate Terraform code and deploy real infrastructure on AWS.
   Mission Brief – What We Are Doing :
   ------------------------------------
     In this project, our challenge is to use GitHub Copilot as an AI assistant to generate a complete Terraform configuration using natural language prompts. 
     Instead of writing Terraform code manually, we will describe what we want, and Copilot will help generate the code. Once the code is ready, we will deploy it to AWS.
     This project is designed for beginners to intermediate developers, so no deep Terraform expertise is required. The entire activity is expected to take around 30 minutes, focusing on learning by doing.

   Technical Requirements – What the Project Must Include :
   --------------------------------------------------------
     While using AI prompts, we will make sure the generated Terraform code includes:
     A security group that allows SSH access on port 22
     A key pair so we can connect to the EC2 instance
     Deployment using the AWS Free Tier with a t2.micro instance
   All infrastructure code should be generated through AI prompts, not written manually.
  
   What We Will Build :
   ---------------------
   As part of this project, we will create:
      A default VPC in the us-west-2 region
   A security group that:
      Allows inbound SSH traffic from anywhere
      Allows all outbound traffic
  An EC2 instance using Amazon Linux
  A key pair for SSH access
  Proper tags for resource identification
  By the end, we will have a fully working EC2 setup created through AI-assisted Terraform code.
  
  Deliverables – What We Need to Submit :
  ----------------------------------------
    At the end of the project, we should have:
       Working Terraform code
       Screenshots of AI (Copilot) interactions
       A brief reflection document explaining our vibe coding experience
    This helps us show both the technical output and the learning process.

  Success Criteria – How We Know It Worked :
  ------------------------------------------
   The project is successful if:
     The EC2 instance is running
     We can SSH into the instance
   All Terraform code was generated using AI prompts

> Our AI ToolChain :
=====================
  To build AI-driven Infrastructure as Code, we use a combination of AI tools and supporting technical tools. Each tool has a clear role in the workflow.
  Primary Tools :                                                                          
    > GitHub copilot : It's our AI coding assistant. It helps us generate Terraform code using natural language and provides smart code completions as we work.                 
    > VsCode : It's our main development environment. This is where we write code, run Terraform commands, and integrate AI tools like Copilot.                            
    > Cursor : It's is an AI-first code editor. It allows us to chat with AI about our code, ask for changes, explanations, or improvements, and iterate quickly in vibe mode.                       
    > Kiro IDE : It's is used for spec-driven development, which we will learn in a later module(module 3). It focuses on structured, specification-based workflows suitable for production systems.
  Supproting Tools :
    > Terraform: Infrastructue as a code we use to define and provision cloud resources.
    > AWS CLI : Cloud Provider interface, Allowing Terraform and our local system to authenticate and interact with AWS services.
    > Git : Version Control, helping us track changes, collaborate with others, and manage our code safely.

> Installation Steps:
  -------------------
    1. Install Visual Studio Code 
    2. Install GitHub Copilot extension 
    3. Authenticate with GitHub account (requires free/paid subscription) 
    4. Install Terraform extension for VS Code 
    5. Configure AWS CLI with Free Tier credentials 
    6. Install HashiCorp Terraform extension 
    Pro Tips: 
      Enable Copilot Labs for enhanced features Configure Copilot to suggest whole functions 
      Use Ctrl+Enter to see all suggestions
 
